
# --- UC1 - Sticky session with Session Persistence 
session persistence can be implemented using a session identifier, such as a cookie or a custom header. 
This mechanism ensures that all requests from a particular client are routed to the same pod for the duration of their session, preventing data inconsistencies.

# --- UC2 - Round Robin Load Balancing
round-robin is one of the default load balancing strategies used by Envoy to forward requests to backend pods. 
sending each new request to the next pod in line, ensuring a balanced distribution without overloading any single instance.

# --- UC3 - Consistent Hash Load Balancing
consistent hashing can be configured so that requests are distributed based on a hash of a key (like a cookie, HTTP header, or client IP). 
Envoy calculates the hash and routes each request to a specific backend, ensuring that the same client consistently lands on the same pod.

# --- UC4 - Path-Based routing with HTTPRoute
Calico Ingress Gateway, uses the HTTPRoute resource to define path-based routing rules. 
You can match on path prefixes, exact paths, or regex-like patterns, and direct requests to the appropriate backend service

# --- UC5 - Canary Deployment with Traffic Splitting
using Calico Ingress Gateway, canary deployments can be implemented through traffic splitting. 
This means you configure routing rules (e.g., via HTTPRoute) to send a specific percentage of traffic to the new version (the canary),
... and the rest to the stable version. 
Over time, the percentage can be increased as confidence in the new version grows.

# --- UC6 - TCP Routing
Calico Ingress Gateway supports TCP routing via Kubernetes Gateway API (e.g., TCPRoute), enabling layer 4 (L4) routing for TCP traffic. 
This allows you to define rules that forward TCP connections to specific backends (like a DB service)

